WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.923
Welcome to the AiGovOps Library.

00:00:02.173 --> 00:00:11.788
It's a governed core for AI agents, wrapped in a connected set of pages that explain it, show it running, and let you operate it.

00:00:12.038 --> 00:00:22.808
This tour walks every page, tells you what you can do at each stop, and shows how to run the whole thing through Jeeves and the governed agents.

00:00:23.058 --> 00:00:28.058
Press play to let it narrate itself, or move at your own pace.

00:00:28.308 --> 00:00:31.385
This is the home page — the hub.

00:00:31.635 --> 00:00:41.250
It frames the Library as six pieces: the vision, the feel, the build, the way it runs, the running core, and how it governs itself.

00:00:41.500 --> 00:00:44.577
Start anywhere; they all point to each other.

00:00:44.827 --> 00:00:52.135
Notice Jeeves waiting at the top — an agent you can ask to do real work from any page.

00:00:52.385 --> 00:00:53.985
Piece one: the Demo.

00:00:54.235 --> 00:01:00.773
This is the story end to end — one loop, two pillars, and a spine called Yes.

00:01:01.023 --> 00:01:07.946
Everyone walks in free, the shelves fill themselves, and when software isn't enough you can borrow a human.

00:01:08.196 --> 00:01:10.888
It's the two-minute why behind everything else.

00:01:11.138 --> 00:01:15.369
Piece two: the Design Book — the experience and visual language.

00:01:15.619 --> 00:01:23.312
The Rooms rendered, each reference mapped to a room, and the principles behind how the governed core looks and feels.

00:01:23.562 --> 00:01:28.562
This is the voice and the look you'll see across the whole Library.

00:01:28.812 --> 00:01:30.412
Piece three: the Rooms.

00:01:30.662 --> 00:01:39.123
Six interactive rooms — Reception, Reading Room, Makerspace, Commons, Human Library, and the Coffee Shop — running live on the governed core.

00:01:39.373 --> 00:01:44.373
Walking the rooms is the friendliest way to feel how the system works.

00:01:44.623 --> 00:01:48.854
Piece four: the Blueprint — the deployable architecture, section by section.

00:01:49.104 --> 00:01:56.412
The principles, the one-core-many-surfaces shape, deployment topologies, the backend, the rooms, the agent-first design, the request lifecycle, and safety.

00:01:56.662 --> 00:01:59.354
This is the engineering source of truth.

00:01:59.604 --> 00:02:04.988
Piece five: the Plan — how agents, skills, and humans actually run the Library.

00:02:05.238 --> 00:02:12.546
The cast of library staff, the skills they wield, the repeatable evidence-producing processes, and the garden of human delight.

00:02:12.796 --> 00:02:14.719
This is the operating manual.

00:02:14.969 --> 00:02:18.815
Piece six: the Control Plane — security, control, and deployment.

00:02:19.065 --> 00:02:25.219
Secrets in tiers, the single sandbox chokepoint, egress allow-lists, and role-scoped oversight, plus the Rev 2026.

00:02:25.469 --> 00:02:27.069
06 decisions.

00:02:27.319 --> 00:02:30.781
This is how the core stays safe by construction.

00:02:31.031 --> 00:02:32.631
Now watch it run.

00:02:32.881 --> 00:02:44.035
The end-to-end demo: a day in the Library across six rooms and nine agents, the human-gated loop, and spend, rate, and blast-radius controls — all on the live ledger.

00:02:44.285 --> 00:02:48.131
This is the demo actually executed — not described, run.

00:02:48.381 --> 00:02:59.150
A risky ask is governed, the right regulations are mapped, an agent earns its dial instead of flipping a switch, and every step leaves a signed, metadata-only receipt.

00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:01.000
This is the proof.

00:03:01.250 --> 00:03:07.788
The Gates, live: a real council, real questions, a real Beacon-signed ledger, and a real human gate.

00:03:08.038 --> 00:03:11.885
Watch verdicts get signed into the ledger as they happen.

00:03:12.135 --> 00:03:13.735
Prefer it slower?

00:03:13.985 --> 00:03:25.908
The recorded walkthrough takes the gates at half speed — nine rooms, their agents, and every Yes, No, or Maybe verdict signed into the ledger, so you can follow each decision.

00:03:26.158 --> 00:03:34.619
A narrated day in the Library: the governed core handling real requests, each step gated and left as a signed, metadata-only receipt.

00:03:34.869 --> 00:03:37.946
A calm, story-shaped view of the same machinery.

00:03:38.196 --> 00:03:48.196
The guided tour is an interactive map of the Library — the six pieces, the running core, and how the Yes-Gate keeps humans holding the keys.

00:03:48.446 --> 00:03:51.138
Take the docent's tour, or wander freely.

00:03:51.388 --> 00:03:53.312
System Pulse is the heartbeat.

00:03:53.562 --> 00:04:03.946
The governed core is exercised on every deploy, emitting a receipt from each Yes-Gate decision — so the milestones and the live engine status are always honest.

00:04:04.196 --> 00:04:16.119
The Build Tickets are the backlog made legible: Ticket 0 — the first safe slice — then the next ten big items, the agent-feature integrations, the scale roadmap, and the milestones.

00:04:16.369 --> 00:04:19.446
This is what's done, what's next, and why.

00:04:19.696 --> 00:04:30.850
The Durability Plan is the honest operations story: the end-to-end design today, why the core was sleeping, the tiered plan to make it durable, and a recommendation in order.

00:04:31.100 --> 00:04:32.700
Candor over comfort.

00:04:32.950 --> 00:04:39.104
The Newsroom carries announcements, releases, and writing on governed AI from Bob Rapp and Ken Johnston.

00:04:39.354 --> 00:04:41.277
It's where the Foundation speaks.

00:04:41.527 --> 00:04:49.988
F-A-I-Friday is a hundred verified, source-cited AI-harm incidents — and crucially, each one carries the specific gate that would have caught it.

00:04:50.238 --> 00:04:52.546
It turns failure into a checklist.

00:04:52.796 --> 00:05:00.873
FailFest rotates daily through those hundred incidents — one a day, each paired with the gate that would have stopped it.

00:05:01.123 --> 00:05:03.046
A steady drip of learn-from-real-scars.

00:05:03.296 --> 00:05:11.758
The Practitioner Test is a ten-question quiz drawn from real harms: read the case, pick the gate verdict, and see the answer.

00:05:12.008 --> 00:05:15.854
It's how you check whether the gate thinking has landed.

00:05:16.104 --> 00:05:20.335
Meet Jeeves — the concierge at the top of every page.

00:05:20.585 --> 00:05:24.431
Jeeves is an agent, not a person, with no gender.

00:05:24.681 --> 00:05:35.835
You ask for an outcome in plain language, and Jeeves does the bureaucracy: it drafts the work, runs anything reversible, and pauses anything irreversible for a human to approve.

00:05:36.085 --> 00:05:38.008
It never holds the keys.

00:05:38.258 --> 00:05:49.027
Try asking Jeeves to draft a pull request, to check which frameworks apply to your model, to run the gate self-test, or to show the latest signed receipts.

00:05:49.277 --> 00:05:55.815
Underneath Jeeves is one loop, run for every effectful action: propose, human-decide, broker, run sandboxed, and verify.

00:05:56.065 --> 00:06:00.296
The agent proposes an intent and the policy engine classifies it.

00:06:00.546 --> 00:06:07.085
If it's irreversible, a human approves or denies — and that decision is itself a signed receipt.

00:06:07.335 --> 00:06:13.488
On approval, a short-lived scoped token is brokered, so the agent never touches a master secret.

00:06:13.738 --> 00:06:22.200
The tool then runs sandboxed, with no ambient network or filesystem, and the result is verified and chained into the signed ledger.

00:06:22.450 --> 00:06:27.065
Reversible work flows straight through; the irreversible always waits for a human.

00:06:27.315 --> 00:06:30.777
You can put your own agent inside this loop.

00:06:31.027 --> 00:06:45.642
Govern Any Agent is the connector: point any M-C-P client — Claude Code, Desktop, Cursor — at the governed core, and its effectful actions inherit the gate, the broker, the sandbox, and a signed receipt for each one.

00:06:45.892 --> 00:06:47.492
Zero dependencies to install.

00:06:47.742 --> 00:06:51.973
To manage it all, the running core ships a Control Room.

00:06:52.223 --> 00:07:14.915
It's one role-scoped surface: an agentic chat where you type a request and the local model drafts a plan you approve inline; a live oversight ledger tailing every signed receipt; a steward-only kill switch that halts in-flight work and signs its own receipt; and a capability dial that sets each member's limits on level, spend, rate, and blast radius.

00:07:15.165 --> 00:07:21.704
Founders see everything and hold the global kill switch; members see and pause only their own work.

00:07:21.954 --> 00:07:34.646
The agents wield a fixed set of governed skills: map which regulations apply, run a security-and-privacy review, audit accessibility, produce a status report, monitor and alert, and sign evidence into the Beacon ledger.

00:07:34.896 --> 00:07:37.204
Each leaves one signed, metadata-only receipt.

00:07:37.454 --> 00:07:47.069
Around them sit read-only runbooks that automate the reversible chores, and an evidence bundle you can export so an auditor verifies the whole history offline.

00:07:47.319 --> 00:07:56.935
The Library is one property among many that Jeeves coordinates — a single agent across the whole AiGovOps estate, each governed by the same Yes-Gate.

00:07:57.185 --> 00:08:03.723
There's the developer group: the Library, the public Foundation site, and the N C W learning camp.

00:08:03.973 --> 00:08:08.204
There's the Community garden, a live app with a real agent.

00:08:08.454 --> 00:08:14.608
There are the evidence and compliance tools — Beacon, Lantern, Umbrella, and Vendor R F I.

00:08:14.858 --> 00:08:20.242
And there's the open-source v4 platform that packages the whole stack to run yourself.

00:08:20.492 --> 00:08:30.492
Each property carries a posture — auto-reversible, where Jeeves runs the prep and a human approves, or propose-only, where a steward initiates and approves every change.

00:08:30.742 --> 00:08:32.665
We'll walk all of it.

00:08:32.915 --> 00:08:36.762
This is the Foundation site — the public front door.

00:08:37.012 --> 00:08:42.396
Its line is: AI governance that runs like engineering, from intentions to verifiable evidence.

00:08:42.646 --> 00:08:56.108
It's a brand surface, so its posture is propose-only: Jeeves drafts every change, but a steward initiates and approves it, and it ships through a pull request and a review gate, never straight to live.

00:08:56.358 --> 00:09:07.512
The ecosystem page is the Foundation's own map of everything — the governed Library, this hub, the membership community, the tools, and the learning camp, all at a glance.

00:09:07.762 --> 00:09:14.300
If this tour is the guided walk, the ecosystem page is the directory you can return to.

00:09:14.550 --> 00:09:20.704
The Frameworks Explorer answers the first question anyone governing AI asks: which rules apply to me?

00:09:20.954 --> 00:09:34.031
Choose your context and it surfaces the relevant frameworks — the E U A I Act, NIST's A I R M F, I S O forty-two thousand one, G D P R, and more.

00:09:34.281 --> 00:09:38.512
It's the human face of the same framework-map the gate runs.

00:09:38.762 --> 00:09:44.915
Alpha is the lab — the ideation-stage projects the Foundation is building next, in the open.

00:09:45.165 --> 00:09:49.396
It's where you see where AiGovOps is heading before it ships.

00:09:49.646 --> 00:09:55.415
The community page is about the people: contributors, sustainers, founding partners, and the open-source projects.

00:09:55.665 --> 00:10:01.819
It's the on-ramp for anyone who wants to help build governed AI, not just use it.

00:10:02.069 --> 00:10:07.069
The blog carries practitioner writing on AI governance, operational compliance, and responsible deployment.

00:10:07.319 --> 00:10:20.781
And behind it all are two people: Bob Rapp and Ken Johnston, who between them have led A I and data work at Microsoft, I B M, G E, Ford, General Motors, Vodafone, and Autonomic.

00:10:21.031 --> 00:10:26.800
Their pages, and an events page for where to meet them, are a click away.

00:10:27.050 --> 00:10:35.896
The Community is the membership garden — and unlike the explainer pages, it's a live application with a real governed agent behind it.

00:10:36.146 --> 00:10:42.300
Members sign in with a magic link and start as applicants until a steward approves them.

00:10:42.550 --> 00:10:48.319
From there, every effect they ask for runs the same gate you've seen all tour.

00:10:48.569 --> 00:10:59.723
New arrivals get a Jeeves-guided start — three pathways, for a new visitor, a member, or a steward — so the first five minutes have a hand to hold.

00:10:59.973 --> 00:11:07.665
Behind the welcome is the live Control Room: one ask, one approval queue, one signed trail for the whole community.

00:11:07.915 --> 00:11:14.454
Beacon is the evidence engine: it discovers governance-relevant activity and signs it into a verifiable, tamper-evident ledger.

00:11:14.704 --> 00:11:19.704
Every receipt you've seen in this tour traces back to a Beacon signature.

00:11:19.954 --> 00:11:26.492
Its posture is propose-only — the signing tool itself is too important to change without a steward.

00:11:26.742 --> 00:11:28.665
Umbrella is the governance compiler.

00:11:28.915 --> 00:11:33.146
Its line is: governance is a pipeline — make it verifiable.

00:11:33.396 --> 00:11:39.935
It compiles forty-plus of the world's A I laws into concrete, checkable controls and signs the evidence.

00:11:40.185 --> 00:11:45.185
When the gate asks what a regulation actually requires, Umbrella is the source.

00:11:45.435 --> 00:11:51.588
Lantern is the third evidence tool — and it's a Python package, not a web page.

00:11:51.838 --> 00:11:59.146
It reads Beacon's signed bundles and turns them into a clear, human-readable report an auditor or steward can use.

00:11:59.396 --> 00:12:09.012
Together the trio tells one story: Beacon discovers and signs, Umbrella compiles frameworks into controls, and Lantern reads the signed evidence back into a report.

00:12:09.262 --> 00:12:22.338
Vendor R F I helps you choose an A I-governance stack like engineering: fifty vendors across five categories, neutral and gap-aware, so you can run a governed request-for-information instead of trusting a sales deck.

00:12:22.588 --> 00:12:26.819
It's where governance reaches outward, to the people you buy from.

00:12:27.069 --> 00:12:36.300
The N C W AI Expo is the learning on-ramp — a deliberately distinct regional brand that brings governed AI to a wider audience.

00:12:36.550 --> 00:12:44.627
It's a one-day community gathering about how North Central Washington uses AI well: for its students, its schools, and its towns.

00:12:44.877 --> 00:12:47.569
Same governance underneath; a friendlier doorway in.

00:12:47.819 --> 00:12:53.973
The centerpiece is the plenary that sets the stakes — AI as a partner in education.

00:12:54.223 --> 00:13:02.685
It contrasts two students, Maria and Jake, walks the real wins and the real harms with citations, and shows a live demo.

00:13:02.935 --> 00:13:05.627
It's the emotional core of the day.

00:13:05.877 --> 00:13:14.723
The Plan lays out the day itself: four breakouts, one centerpiece plenary, and a room schedule grid — the Expo runs August eleventh.

00:13:14.973 --> 00:13:18.819
This is how a community actually convenes around governed AI.

00:13:19.069 --> 00:13:26.377
The mini-camps are hands-on: thirty-minute sessions built from five real North Central Washington scenarios, filterable by scenario and audience.

00:13:26.627 --> 00:13:31.242
This is where it stops being theory and people actually try it.

00:13:31.492 --> 00:13:39.954
Courses are how you keep going after the Expo — the AiGovOps community learning paths, including governed agents and the read-act loop.

00:13:40.204 --> 00:13:42.896
The single day becomes an ongoing practice.

00:13:43.146 --> 00:13:56.223
And the Pledge ties it together: the N C W AI Partnership Pledge, version one point zero — seven commitments, signed by the citizens, educators, business owners, and community leaders of North Central Washington.

00:13:56.473 --> 00:13:58.396
Governance, made personal and public.

00:13:58.646 --> 00:14:00.569
Finally, the open-source v4 platform.

00:14:00.819 --> 00:14:09.665
This is the whole stack — Beacon, Lantern, and Umbrella, orchestrated by Jeeves — packaged to install and run yourself in one command.

00:14:09.915 --> 00:14:16.838
Its creed is the spine of everything you've seen: get to Yes, stay at Yes, recover to Yes.

00:14:17.088 --> 00:14:18.688
No maybes allowed.

00:14:18.938 --> 00:14:20.862
That's AiGovOps, end to end.

00:14:21.112 --> 00:14:33.035
You've seen the Library's six pieces, watched the governed core run with every step signed, met Jeeves, learned the Yes-Gate loop, connected your own agent, and seen how to operate it.

00:14:33.285 --> 00:14:49.054
Then the whole estate: the Foundation site and all its pages, the membership garden, the tools — Beacon, Umbrella, Lantern, and Vendor R F I — the N C W learning camp, and the open-source v4 platform you can run yourself.

00:14:49.304 --> 00:14:55.073
One agent does the bureaucracy across all of it; a human always holds the keys.

00:14:55.323 --> 00:15:02.631
Good next stops: watch a real run, connect your agent, or just ask Jeeves to do something for you.

00:15:02.881 --> 00:15:04.481
Welcome to AiGovOps.
